SIMPLE: procrastinate
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Procrastinate
<hw>Pro*cras"ti*nate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Procrastinated</conjf>
<pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Procrastinating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>procrastinatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>procrastinare</ets> to
procrastinate; <ets>pro</ets> forward + <ets>crastinus</ets> of
to-morrow, fr. <ets>cras</ets> to-morrow.]</ety> <def>To put off till
to-morrow, or from day to day; to defer; to postpone; to delay; <as>as,
to <ex>procrastinate</ex> repentance</as>.</def> <rj><au>Dr. H.
More.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Hopeless and helpless Aegeon wend,⟦br⟧
But to <qex>procrastinate</qex> his lifeless end.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To postpone; adjourn; defer; delay; retard;
protract; prolong.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Procrastinate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Procrastinate
<hw>Pro*cras"ti*nate</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To delay; to be
dilatory.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I <qex>procrastinate</qex> more than I did twenty years ago.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Procrastination</ent>⟦br⟧
